Boil a #large pot{} of salted @water{to taste} for the pasta.

When boiling, add the @dried rigatoni{180%g} and bring back to the boil. Cook until
softened, ~{12%minutes}.

Drain in a #colander{} and return to the pot, off the heat. Drizzle with
@oil{to taste} and toss to prevent sticking.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and finely chop the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and finely
chopped). Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic
press{}).

Halve and deseed the @bell pepper{1}(halved, deseeded and chopped into 2cm
chunks). Chop into 2cm chunks.

> TIP: To save time you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, place a #pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Fry the onion until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add the @Irish pork mince{240%g}, garlic and @paprika{1%sachet}.

Fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Break the pork up with a #spoon{} as it
cooks. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw mince. Mince is cooked
> when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the pepper, @passata{1%pack}, @Worcester sauce{1%sachet} and 1/2 tsp
@sugar{1/2%tsp}. Cook for ~{6-8%minutes}.

Add the cooked pasta to the pan along with half the @grated cheese{50%g}.

Mix well to evenly coat.

Taste and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Cook until the pasta is warmed through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @parsley{5%g}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Divide the pasta between deep #plates{} or #bowls{}.

Top with a dollop of @creme fraiche{65%g}.

Garnish with the parsley and remaining cheese.